07481nam a22008895i 9780748637331DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486373317 a10.1515/97807486373312doi  a(DE-B1597)615156  a(OCoLC)1306539495  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aREL0370102bisacsh  aBE 8660qSEPA2rvk1 aLange, Christian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPublic Violence in Islamic Societies :bPower, Discipline, and the Construction of the Public Sphere, 7th-19th Centuries CE /cChristian Lange, Maribel Fierro. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Spatial, ritual and representational aspects of public violence in Islamic societies (7th–19th centuries CE) -- tPART I Public violence and the construction of the public sphere -- t1 The case of Jaʿd b. Dirham and the punishment of ‘heretics’ in the early caliphate -- t2 Qāḍīs and the political use of the maẓālim jurisdiction under the ʿAbbāsids -- t3 From revolutionary violence to state violence: the Fāṭimids (297–567/909–1171) -- t4 Actions speak louder than words: reactions to lampoons and abusive poetry in medieval Arabic society -- tPART II Ritual dimensions of violence -- t5 Reveal or conceal: public humiliation and banishment as punishments in early Islamic times -- t6 Emulating Abraham: the Fāṭimid al-Qāʾim and the Umayyad ʿAbd al-Raḥmān III -- t7 Where on earth is hell? State punishment and eschatology in the Islamic middle period -- t8 Justice, crime and punishment in 10th/16th-century Morocco -- tPART III Representations of public violence -- t9 Responses to crucifixion in the Islamic world (1st–7th/7th–13th centuries) -- t10 Violence and the prince: the case of the Aghlabid Amīr Ibrāhīm II (261–89/875–902) -- t11 Concepts of justice and the catalogue of punishments under the Sultans of Delhi (7th–8th/13th–14th centuries) -- t12 Public violence, state legitimacy: the Iqāmat al-ḥudūd and the sacred state -- t13 Violence in Islamic societies through the eyes of non-Muslim travellers: Morocco in the 19th and early 20th centuries -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis exploration of the role of violence in the history of Islamic societies considers the subject particularly in the context of its implementation as a political strategy to claim power over the public sphere.Violence, both among Muslims and between Muslims and non-Muslims, has been the object of research in the past, as in the case of jihad, martyrdom, rebellion or criminal law. This book goes beyond these concerns in addressing, in a comprehensive and cross-disciplinary fashion, how violence has functioned as a basic principle of Islamic social and political organization in a variety of historical and geographical contexts.Contributions trace the use of violence by governments in the history of Islam, shed light on legal views of violence, and discuss artistic and religious responses. Authors lay out a spectrum of attitudes rather than trying to define an Islamic doctrine of violence. Bringing together some of the most substantive and innovative scholarship on this important topic to date, this volume contributes to the growing interest, both scholarly and general, in the question of Muslim attitudes toward violence.Key Features:Satisfies increasing interest in the issue of Muslim attitudes toward violence, highlighting the complexity of this topic and the diversity of Muslim attitudes toward violence.Offers an overview of the economy of violence under the various dynasties/governments that shaped the history of Islamic civilization.Incorporates innovative and novel approaches to violence as a feature of social and political organization.Contributions are written by well-known scholars in the field, providing up-to-date scholarship that spans languages (primary and secondary) and academic disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIslam and social problemsxHistory. 0aMuslimsxSocial conditions. 0aPolitical violencexHistoryxIslamic countries. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryxIslamic countries. 0aViolencexHistoryxIslamic countries. 0aViolencexPublic opinionxHistoryxIslamic countries. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh1 aAuer, Blain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFierro, Maribel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFierro, Maribel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleave, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawting, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLange, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLev, Yaacov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarín, Manuela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMediano, Fernando Rodríguez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNef, Annliese, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowson, Everett K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeidensticker, Tilman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzombathy, Zoltán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTillier, Mathieu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eB